http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 5 Jul 012
Source: New Scientist [summarised, edited]
http://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22016-footandmouth-disease-stalks-egypt.html


Foot-and-mouth disease stalks Egypt
-----------------------------------
A new strain of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) in Egypt could aggravate discontent among the rural poor and prolong the country's political turmoil.

As Egypt struggles to make a vaccine, agriculture experts fear a vicious circle has begun: political disarray helps spread animal disease, which deepens poverty and discontent -- and breeds more political disarray. Meanwhile neighbouring countries fear Egypt's virus could soon reach them.

FMD kills young cattle, buffalo, and other ruminants, weakens older ones and slashes farms' productivity. At a meeting in Bangkok, Thailand, last week, the member countries of the UN Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) launched a plan to get FMD under control worldwide by 2027 [see 20120628.1184291]. Yet the FAO cannot get money to have vaccine made out of existing stocks of ingredients for the Egyptian outbreak.

Egypt already harbours 2 strains of the FMD virus [serotypes O and A], but its livestock have some resistance to them, through either exposure or vaccination. They have none to the new strain, SAT2.

In February [2012], migrant herders also brought SAT2 to Libya, although there are slight genetic differences between the viruses in Libya and Egypt. Political upheaval in both countries means "the ability to do the right surveillance and control has been quite diminished," says Juan Lubroth, head of animal health at the FAO in Rome. He fears what could also happen if the virus turns up in Syria or Iraq.

In Egypt, where endemic H5N1 bird flu decimates poultry as well, the new losses have inflated meat prices, adding to discontent -- frustrated farmers have dumped dead animals outside government veterinary offices. New cases of FMD are now on the wane, but without widespread vaccination, says Lubroth, there will be successive waves of the disease.

With 14 million livestock at risk, Egypt says it has imported 4 million doses of SAT2 vaccine, from Botswana and the vaccine firm Merial, and that it has made 4.6 million more -- although it has had to dispense with time-consuming quality controls. Some 750 000 livestock have received the vaccine, but they will need a booster dose before they are immune, and the effectiveness of the campaign may not be clear until the next wave hits. Given Egypt's limited capacity to administer the vaccine strategically to stop the new strain spreading, for instance at live animal markets, it will simply persist, Lubroth fears.

That puts the whole region at risk: FMD is the most contagious animal virus known. European Union officials are said to be preparing contingency plans. Israel has vaccinated livestock along its southern border and given vaccine to Palestinian authorities, who have contained the virus after infected animals came to Gaza through smuggling tunnels from Egypt.

Although FAO member countries have endorsed its plan to stop outbreaks over the next 15 years using vaccination, there are no plans to eradicate the virus worldwide, partly because it persists in wildlife, such as buffalo. Regions that have eliminated it, like western Europe and North America, remain at risk from the 100 countries where outbreaks continue to occur.

[byline: Debora MacKenzie]

