[Egypt has officially submitted 5 reports on the current epizootic to the OIE, addressing a total of 49 outbreaks as of 24 Jun 2012. According to the reports, the accumulated number of cases is as follows: buffaloes -- 1955 clinical cases, 56 deaths; cattle -- 1070 cases, 83 deaths; sheep/goats -- 38 cases, 26 deaths). According to the reports, the Egyptian SAT-2 epizootic started on 12 Feb 2012, was confirmed on 4 Mar 2012, and was 1st reported to the OIE on 14 Mar 2012. The epizootic spread throughout the entire country; all 5 reports and an interactive map are available at http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=11748.

Egyptian press, citing the minister of agriculture, have mentioned numbers of cases and deaths which were at least 30-fold higher.

There are at least 2 other FMD virus circulating in Egypt, of serotypes O and A; this may have aggravated the situation. In this respect, subscribers are referred to the recent statement of WRLFMD:

"In addition to the recent cases due to serotype SAT2, a new FMDV type A lineage (which we have named A/AFRICA/G-IV[ISM-12]) was also detected in Egypt in 2012. This was found to be most closely related to viruses from Sudan and Eritrea suggesting yet another recent introduction of FMDV from sub-Saharan Africa.

"Therefore, the FMD situation in Egypt has become extremely complex with the presence of at least 5 distinct FMDV lineages between 2010 and 2012, requiring at least 3 different vaccine virus strains."

For the details of the different FMDV lineages present in the region in the last few years, subscribers are referred to the full statement, including the descriptions of the above mentioned strains, in posting 20120507.1125683.

In view of the difficulties to perform in Egypt a detailed surveillance, the actual pathogenicity and infectivity of the circulating FMD SAT-2 virus strain are in need of further study. Notably, the virus was swiftly controlled by the Palestinian veterinary authorities in the Gaza strip, where the disease remained restricted to the 1st 2 foci in cattle holdings adjacent to the Egyptian border, and did not spread. Interestingly, the (about 80 000, unvaccinated) sheep and goats in the Gaza strip have, reportedly, remained (clinically) unaffected. One might wish for serological surveillance to be carried out in the said small-ruminant population, to try to check if subclinical infection has taken place. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1zkM.]
